      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Morbid is, as mentioned prior, a Souls-like title, with shrines to upgrade gear (a clear homage to bonfires), a wheel of familiar four slots, the typical limited healing items and gimmick of enemies that come back upon death. The beats of the series are there, just transplanted onto the isometric backdrop with shocking ease, to the same quality and care that ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Salt and Sanctuary",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " did, albeit with 2D Metroidvanias. The boss fights are epic and grand in scale whilst the enemies provide that sweet interim challenge that makes the trek between health bars engaging. There’s also no need to grind out to keep momentum but doing so definitely helps.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "With plenty taken from the Souls series, the most noteworthy inclusion is found in ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Morbid",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "’s weapon design, with 25 on offer that all provide their own unique playstyles, whether that’s the swifter small blades of agile thieves or the more clunky and slow-moving hammers that deal crushing blows at the cost of stamina. The selection is fairly limited but diverse enough that the limitations aren’t glaring, which is perfect.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2020/12/image-12.png",
        "width": 1280,
        "height": 720
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Top-down is an interesting take, and for the most part, it translates well. Howver, in the adaptation of a Souls formula onto an isometric canvas, part of the charm that comes with this camera style was lost. The twist is a treat, for sure, but that itch of tightly-knit, packed to the brim world design isn’t quite there which makes you crave for the classics like Fallout or the brand-new Baldur’s Gate sequel. There’s not a whole lot to be found, with everything feeling a touch barren, leaving the interaction to be very surface level with visuals coming first and foremost.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
